article.headline: Radmanovic scores 25
article.linkText: Sonics' bench stays home, but Seattle wins
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Despite holding the Washington Wizards to two dozen points in the first half, the Seattle SuperSonics had to sweat this one out down the stretch. Vladimir Radmanovic scored a season-high 25 points, Rashard Lewis had 24 and Ronald Murray topped 20 points for the ninth time this season in Seattle's 88-85 victory Sunday night. "I think a team needs breaks and we got a break tonight, and one that we probably shouldn't be getting," Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. Before the game, McMillan stressed that his team needed to improve its execution in the fourth quarter. They did, but it came at the very end after blowing an 18-point second-half lead. "We get a W and almost gave this game away," McMillan said. "We gave up a 28-point third quarter and a 33-point fourth quarter." Radmanovic split a pair of free throws with 17 seconds left to increase Seattle's lead to 84-81. Ansu Sesay then hit one of two free throws to increase the lead to four with 11.9 seconds to play. It was the only point scored by Seattle's non-starters. Jared Jeffries hit a turnaround 3-pointer with 8.9 seconds left, Lewis made two free throws and Juan Dixon attempted to tie the game with a 3-pointer but was off the mark. Dixon came off the bench to score a season-high 17 points. Kwame Brown also had 17. Gilbert Arenas had 15 before missing the final 4:36 with an abdominal strain. "He is hurt pretty good, and we probably won't have him the rest of the trip," said Wizards coach Eddie Jordan, whose team finishes a four-game trip with back-to-back games against the Trail Blazers and Lakers. "I don't want to misdiagnose it, but it's bad. It's bad right now." Arenas will undergo further examination Monday. "I was making a spin move and then I felt something pop," said Arenas, Washington's leading scorer. "I've played with a lot of injuries before, so I'm not too worried about it right now." The Wizards have lost six of their last eight games, while the Sonics snapped a two-game losing streak. They had lost three straight at home. "It was hard to come back, but fortunately we came back," Radmanovic said. "We needed this break. We lost three straight at home, and that's hard for a team. We're a team that still has a winning record (7-4), but when you lose at home you lose confidence." Seattle led most of the game, holding the Wizards to a franchise-low 24 first-half points. Radmanovic's 3-pointer pushed the lead to 50-33 with 5:17 to play in the third quarter before Washington closed the gap in a hurry and took a 63-62 lead on Dixon's 3-pointer with 9:25 to play. "In the second half, we came out with a lot more energy," said Dixon. "That was the difference. We played with some passion, and finally started making some shots in the second half."< ^Notes@: Seattle's injured F Nick Collison traveled to New York on Sunday to have his surgically repaired left shoulder checked and to set a date for surgery on his right shoulder. ... Arenas couldn't make up his mind on his footwear. He changed shoes three times in the first half alone. He started the game wearing black shoes and no socks, then added socks and went to two different pairs of white shoes. ... The Wizards had scored 25 in a half three different times, the last being Dec. 22, 1985, against the New York Knicks.
